@Sam T
Obviously, we’re transliterating from an entirely different writing system, so there’s theoretically some flexibility in the Latin spelling, but I think you’re probably confusing what the clue is asking for with what literally means “older brother” or, by extension, what is used as a term of address for any male person perceived as slightly older than the speaker (typically when said speaker is female—“hyeong” is used by male speakers, instead). Here, APPA is a term of address for one’s father (regardless of the speaker’s gender, I believe). I don’t think 아 (‘a’) and 오 (‘o’) tend to vary between different romanization systems, either those used in scholarship or ad hoc in subtitling.

(In the song “Gangnam Style,” omnipresent a decade ago, Psy uses “oppa” somewhat non-standardly to refer to himself in a quasi-first-person manner because his ironic playboy persona in the song is exhorting attractive young women to think of him as a young and virile [non-literal] older brother type, even though his age and appearance, as seen in the music video, would generally place him firmly in “ajusshi” [“uncle,” middle-aged man] territory.)

