@Al  in Pittsburgh
I do remember the 9/5 factor (plus 32), hence my daily a.m. mutterings. Rather than multiply by 9 and then divide by 5—which burns too many brain calories when you're doing numbers not divisible by 5—I multiply by 2, then subtract a tenth of that number, which is the same as x1.8 (plus 32), but super quick to do in your head without resorting to your phone. My biggest issue with getting used to Celsius is that remembering that 20C is 68F (i.e. needing my husband's bathrobe) and that 25C is 77F ("A/c! Turn on the a/c!") leaves several levels of comfort  to be decided in between, sometimes needing (horrors!) the decimal point or 3 significant figures.

OK, all of this is a bit tongue in cheek, but it's still true that apparently I'm better at on-the-fly conversions that I am at adapting to a new system of measurement. My husband the engineer is fully switched to Celsius and all things metric; I continue having my weather app in Fahrenheit and my navigation in miles. Maybe if my grant and thus my invitation to stay here are extended, I'll try adapting a bit harder. In the meantime, there will be a lot of simple arithmetic in my immediate future...

